The most common sense and uniform procedure will be to quarantine anyone entering for a period of days some for 14 days, some for 10 days. This is irrespective of whether that person has a visa or not. After that, then other procedural steps will be checked. This, I think, should be considered on Djoko's entry. If there is a uniform, norm, or conditions taken, I think all of these debacles would have been avoided. The PM states rules are rules, nobody is above the law, all very well and good, but set a clear series of rules, laws, stick to it, and put the fear of God into whoever breaks them, Djoko included.
   This inability to handle a case like Djoko, flip flops, sends a chill down every right-thinking soul in the world, if Aus cannot stand firm on a matter like this, how can we expect a commitment on defending Taiwan against China?
